Module 1: Session 3 - Speaking, Presenting & Holding the Room (2 Hours)

Complete Facilitator Materials & Student Resources

PRE-SESSION SETUP

Materials Needed:

  • CRITICAL: Phone/camera on tripod for recording (or laptop webcam)
  • Large timer visible to all students
  • Projector for video playback
  • Role cards for meeting simulation (printed, see below)
  • Observation rubrics (1 per student)
  • Whiteboard for capturing feedback
  • Name tags for meeting simulation roles

Room Setup:

  • Clear space at front for presentations
  • Meeting simulation area with 5-6 chairs arranged in small circle
  • Recording equipment positioned to capture speakers

Pre-Session Task:

  • Students should have prepared 3-minute mini-pitches (homework from Session 2)
  • Confirm recording equipment works (test before session starts)

OPENING: THE 60-SECOND INTRODUCTION (20 minutes)

âFor the past two sessions, we focused on writing. Today is about speakingâspecifically, how to project confidence and clarity when youâre standing in front of people. Weâre going to start by making everyone uncomfortable.â

The Challenge:

Display on screen:

THE 60-SECOND PROFESSIONAL INTRODUCTION

You have 60 seconds to introduce yourself professionally.

Must include:
- Your name and background
- Your current role or area of study
- One relevant skill or strength
- What you bring to a team

Rules:
- No filler words ("um," "uh," "like," "basically," "actually")
- Maintain eye contact with the group
- Stand still (no pacing or swaying)
- End with confidence (don't trail off)

Each person will go. We'll give feedback after each introduction.

Process (15 minutes for ~25 students):

Facilitator demonstrates first:

[Stand confidently at front]

âGood morning. Iâm [Name], and Iâve spent the past eight years training professionals in communication and business skills. My strength is breaking down complex workplace dynamics into practical techniques you can use immediately. What I bring to this program is real-world experienceâIâve worked with over 200 companies across India, and I know exactly what employers are looking for in graduates. Iâm here to make sure youâre ready to impress from Day One.â

[Pause, then explain]

âNotice: - I stated my name clearly (youâd be surprised how many people mumble this) - I didnât say âHello everyone, hope youâre all doing wellâ (wasted time) - I quantified my experience (8 years, 200 companies = credibility) - I told you whatâs in it for you (not just about me) - I ended definitively (no âsoâ¦ yeahâ¦â)

Student Introductions:

  • Students present in order (alphabetical or by seating)
  • Keep strict 60-second limit (gently cut off if they exceed)
  • After EVERY introduction, get 2-3 pieces of quick feedback from peers:
    • âWhat did this person do well?â
    • âOne small improvement?â

Facilitator Captures Patterns (last 5 minutes):

Write on whiteboard as you observe:

Common Strengths: - Clear voice - Good eye contact - Specific examples

Common Issues: - Filler words (especially âactually,â âbasically,â âsoâ) - Rushing through (nervous speed) - Weak endings (âSoâ¦ yeahâ¦ thatâs itâ) - Looking at floor or ceiling instead of audience

âThree quick tips for any professional introduction:

  1. Pace yourself: Most people speed up when nervous. Deliberately slow down 10% from your natural pace.

  2. The 2-second rule: After you state your name, pause for two full seconds before continuing. It gives people time to register who you are.

  3. Own your space: Plant your feet shoulder-width apart. It feels weird but looks confident. Pacing or swaying makes you look nervous even if youâre not.â

TIME LIMIT: 15 MINUTES

Assign Roles (2 minutes)

How to choose participants:

  • Manager: Pick someone who showed confidence in introduction exercise
  • Arjun (Marketing): Pick someone comfortable speaking up
  • Priya (Product): Pick someone quieter/more reserved (this role will challenge them)
  • Karan (Customer Success): Pick someone expressive
  • Finance Observer: Pick someone with good observation skills

Observer Instructions (3 minutes)

For students NOT in the meeting, distribute observation rubric:

MEETING OBSERVATION RUBRIC

Watch for these behaviors and note specific examples:

EXECUTIVE PRESENCE:
- Who maintained confident body language?
- Who made effective eye contact?
- Who had physical tells of nervousness? (fidgeting, looking down)

COMMUNICATION EFFECTIVENESS:
- Who stated their case most clearly?
- Who used data vs. who used emotion?
- Who adapted their message based on the room's reaction?

MEETING DYNAMICS:
- Who got interrupted? How did they respond?
- Who interrupted others?
- Who built on others' points vs. who just waited to talk?
- How did the manager handle conflicts?

PERSUASION TACTICS:
- Who made the strongest case? Why?
- Who undermined their own position? How?
- Who showed they understood others' perspectives?

Note 2-3 specific moments that stood out (timestamp them if possible).

  • Facilitator: Start recording immediately
  • Let it run: Donât intervene unless it goes completely off track
  • Watch for: Who gets talked over, who dominates, how conflict is handled
  • Keep visible timerâstop at exactly 15 minutes

  2. A moment of interruption (How did the interrupted person respond?)

  1. The confidence-competence gap: The most confident speaker isnât always right. But confidence gets airtime.

  2. Gender/cultural dynamics: In Indian corporate culture, women and younger employees often struggle to be heard. This isnât fixed by âbeing more confidentââit requires awareness and active intervention.

MASTERING DIFFICULT CONVERSATIONS (30 minutes)

Facilitator Transition:

âThat meeting simulation showed us group dynamics. Now letâs tackle one-on-one situations where you need to be direct but respectfulâwhich is one of the hardest professional skills.â

The Framework (10 minutes)

Display and explain:

THE FOUR-PART DIFFICULT CONVERSATION STRUCTURE

1. STATE THE ISSUE OBJECTIVELY
   - Facts only, no judgment
   - Specific behavior, not character
   - Bad: "You're always late"
   - Good: "You've arrived 15-20 minutes after our agreed meeting time three times this week"

2. ACKNOWLEDGE THEIR PERSPECTIVE
   - Shows you're not attacking
   - Opens dialogue instead of creating defense
   - "I realize you might have reasons I'm not aware of"
   - "Help me understand what's happening on your end"

3. EXPLAIN THE IMPACT
   - Make it concrete, not abstract
   - Bad: "It's unprofessional"
   - Good: "When you're late, the client waits, which reflects poorly on our team"

4. PROPOSE A SOLUTION + INVITE DIALOGUE
   - Don't just complainâwhat should change?
   - Make it collaborative
   - "Going forward, can we..."
   - "What would help you..."

Real Examples (Show on screen):

Scenario 1: Giving peer feedback

Bad approach: âHey, your work on the last project wasnât great. You need to pay more attention to quality.â

Good approach: âI wanted to talk about the client report from last week. I noticed the financial projections in Section 3 didnât match the executive summaryâthe numbers were off by about 15%. I know we were under tight deadline pressure. Going forward, can we build in a peer review step before submissions? Iâm happy to review yours if you review mine.â

Scenario 2: Disagreeing with your manager

Bad approach: âI donât think that strategy will work.â

Good approach: âI understand the rationale for targeting Tier 2 cities first. I have a concern about the timelineâbased on our previous expansion to Pune, setup took 8 weeks, not 4. Would it be worth discussing a phased approach so we donât over-promise to the client?â

Scenario 3: Declining a senior colleagueâs request

Bad approach: âSorry, I canât help with that.â

Good approach: âI appreciate you thinking of me for this project. Unfortunately, Iâm at capacity through end of month with three client deadlines. I donât want to commit and deliver late or below standard. Ravi in the analytics team mentioned he has lighter load this weekâwould you like me to introduce you?â

Instructions for Role-Play:

Display on screen:

ROLE-PLAY INSTRUCTIONS:

1. Person A: You're having the difficult conversation
   - Use the 4-part framework
   - Stay calm and professional
   - Practice OUT LOUD (don't just think through it)

2. Person B: You're receiving the feedback
   - React authentically (defensive? Understanding? Surprised?)
   - Don't make it easyâpush back a little
   - Real people often get defensive first

3. Run the conversation for 4-5 minutes

4. Then switch: Person B gives feedback to Person A on:
   - What felt respectful vs. attacking?
   - What would have made you more receptive?
   - What specific phrase worked well?

5. Then REVERSE roles and run the scenario again with improvements

Facilitator circulates, listening and coaching:

Common issues to address: - Too apologetic (âIâm so sorry to bring this up, I feel terribleâ¦â) - Too aggressive (âYou need to stop doing thisâ) - Too vague (âI just wanted to check in about the project stuffâ) - Not listening to the response (preparing rebuttal instead)

âWhat was harder than you expected?â (Expected answers: staying calm, not getting defensive when receiving feedback, finding the right words)

Key Takeaway:

âDifficult conversations fail when they feel like attacks. They succeed when they feel like problem-solving. The framework helps you stay in problem-solving mode even when emotions are high.â

THE MINI-PRESENTATION CHALLENGE (30 minutes)

âYouâve all prepared 3-minute pitches. Now youâll present them in small groups of 4-5 people. This is about delivery, not content. Weâre looking for: confident opening, clear structure, eye contact, vocal variety, and strong closing.â

WHAT WORKED BEST:


ONE IMPROVEMENT:

  • Others in group complete feedback rubric
  • After each presentation: 2 minutes for group to share feedback
  • Timekeeper enforces limits (gently)

âWho saw a presentation that really grabbed them? What made it work?â

FACILITATOR NOTES & TEACHING TIPS

Critical Success Factors:

  1. Recording quality matters: Test equipment before session. Students need to clearly see themselves on playback for this to work.

  2. Psychological safety: Some students will be very nervous about speaking. Emphasize: âEveryone feels this way. Nervousness is normal. Weâre all learning together.â

  3. Managing dominant personalities: In the meeting simulation, the âArjunâ role might actually dominate. Thatâs okayâit makes the debrief more powerful. Donât intervene unless it becomes disrespectful.

Time Flexibility:

Differentiation:

  • For nervous speakers: Put them in observer role first, then in small group presentations (lower stakes)

Assessment Signals:
